Start by drawing what you like, draw a scene or a character from an anime or videogame you like, some pose you think all the time, etc.
Try to do something "big", like drawing a whole body that uses a whole page/canvas and not just a small corner of it, this is what separates a doodle from a drawing
Then search for techniques and apply those to your drawings, almost all the work in drawing is learning techniques and how to use the tools available to you, everything else is just practice that becomes second nature
Remember that you have google and you can search whatever you have trouble with
https://www.ctrlpaint.com/

Speaking as an artist, the "easy" source of money is just drawing OCs/popular characters, futa, and getting enough of a following who's into the stuff you draw. The "furry comms" meme is still true, kind of, but at least with the commissioners I deal with they're usually less discerning and tend to be more interested in cute wamenz as opposed to just strictly anthros. Drawing anthros wasn't "easy money" because it was furry, it got that reputation because furries tend to have OCs and fursonas and those people wanted artists to draw them for them.

I wouldn't say hmofa is any less unattractive to anthro on anthro in the comm scene — aside from getting comms of fursonas fucking fursonas. Basically everyone these days are fine with a human self-insert fucking the latest flavour of the month or whatever. Unless you're grinding those fursona bucks, you don't need to draw furbois unless you actually want to.

>>68427736
>theres always something to learn and despite all the improvments its like the cap to be "good" is going further away
You're kind of right in some respect, but it's important to note that it gets increasingly easier to reach this "cap" now that a path has been set by other artists. Digital art has been pushed far over the last two decades, but it's not like it'd take decades to get to where artists are drawing now, too. Just look at their art and study it. We're standing on the shoulders of giants.

AI has a chance to threaten our jobs. But that can be said about any profession tbqh. Just look at the anxiety coders already have about AI replacing them. As it is now, though, it's not even really close. The appeal of AI is that it's fun to fuck around with it, it's why I maintain a subscription to NovelAI at the moment (are there better paid alternatives now?), but I don't think anyone with floor-level tastes has any preference for it.
